Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
addDummyBoundaryWires(25.10)                      addDummyBoundaryWires(25.10)

Name
       addDummyBoundaryWires  -  Add wires on the first and last tracks in the
       direction parallel to preferred routing direction with specified layers

Syntax
       addDummyBoundaryWires

       [-help]

       -layers <layerName> | { <layerNameList ...> }

       [-masks <maskNumber> | { <maskNumberList ...> }]

       [-shape {blockring | blockagewire | blockwire  |  corewire  |  drcfill|
       fillwireopc  |  fillwire | followpin | iowire | none | padring | ring |
       stripe} ]

       [-shortWires <wireLength> | { <wireLengthList ...> }]

       [-space <spaceValue> | { <spaceValueList ...> }]

       Add wires on the first and last tracks in  the  direction  parallel  to
       preferred routing direction with specified layers.

       Note: DRC rules define forbidden regions near the design boundary edges
       that  are  parallel  to the preferred routing direction of a layer. Any
       wires in these regions cannot project to the design boundary  directly.
       Using  the  addDummyBoundaryWires command you can add wires that shadow
       the design boundary such that no routing wires in the forbidden regions
       can project to the design boundary. This helps to avoid DRC violations.

       Note: The addDummyBoundaryWires command enables  long  dummy  wires  to
       honor route blockages by default.

       Note:  The  addDummyBoundaryWire  command  honors routing blockages and
       adds dummy wires along the routing blockages when the track  box  over-
       laps  with them. The dummy wires do not cross partial routing blockages
       around the design boundary. It keeps the wires at the boundary and dis-
       continues them when there is a routing blockage.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes the type  and  default
              information  for each addDummyBoundaryWires parameter. For a de-
              tailed description of the command and all of its parameters, use
              the man command:

              man addDummyBoundaryWires

       -layers <layerName> | { <layerNameList ...> }
              Specifies the layers on  which  the  dummy  boundary  wires  are
              added.

              Note:   The  net name of the dummy wires is "_BOUNDARY_WIRES_RE-
              SERVED".

              Note:  You can specify the layerName as a  number,  abbreviation
              or as a layer name defined in LEF. For example, layerName can be
              specified as 2, M2 or Metal2.

              addDummyBoundaryWires -layers {metal2 metal3} //full name works

              addDummyBoundaryWires -layers {M2 M3} //abbreviated name works

              addDummyBoundaryWires -layers {2 3} ///layer number works

              Data_type: string, required

       -masks <maskNumber> | { <maskNumberList> ... }
              Specifies  one or multiple mask numbers which short dummy bound-
              ary wires snap to. The number of specified  mask  values  should
              match the number of the specified layers in option layers.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -shape {blockring | blockagewire | blockwire | corewire | drcfill|
       fillwireopc | fillwire | followpin | iowire | none | padring | ring |
       stripe}
              Specifies the shape of the dummy boundary wires.

              Default: none

              Data_type: string, optional

       -shortWires <wireLength> | { <wireLengthList ...> }
              Specifies one or multiple set of lengths of short dummy boundary
              wires and space between them. The number of specified shortWires
              values  should be twice of the number of specified layers in op-
              tion layers.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -space <spaceValue> | { <spaceValueList ...> }
              Specifies one or multiple space values to design boundary.

              Note: The space value is the distance between the design  bound-
              ary  and  the  start or end of the wire for 90 corner. The space
              value does not apply to 270 corner.

              Default: 0

              Data_type: string, optional

Examples
              * The following command adds dummy wires on  layers  metal2  and
                metal3:

                addDummyBoundaryWires -layers {M2 M3}

              * The  following  command  adds dummy wires on layers metal2 and
                metal3. Dummy wires will honor route blockages by  default  on
                Metal3 :

                addDummyBoundaryWires -layers {M2 M3}

              * The  following  command  adds  dummy wires with space value on
                layers metal2 and metal3:

                addDummyBoundaryWires -layers {M2 M3} -space {0.1 0.2}

              * The following command adds long  dummy  wires  with  specified
                space  and  short dummy wires with specified length, space and
                mask on layers metal2:

                addDummyBoundaryWires -layers M2 -space 0.1 -shortWires  {0.15
                0.2} -masks 1

